04979nam a22007095i 9780804796309DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202015cau    fo  d z      eng d  a2015007352  a97808047963097 a10.1515/97808047963092doi  a(DE-B1597)563894  a(OCoLC)1198930127  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA00aDS432.G87bM58 2016 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a301.0954/14223  aLB 36385qBVB2rvk1 aMiddleton, Townsend, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Demands of Recognition :bState Anthropology and Ethnopolitics in Darjeeling /cTownsend Middleton. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSouth Asia in Motion00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tLIST OF ILLUSTRATIONS -- tACKNOWLEDGMENTS -- tTECHNICAL NOTES -- tINTRODUCTION. BECOMING TRIBAL IN DARJEELING: An Introduction to the Ethno-Contemporary -- tCHAPTER 1. A SEARCHING POLITICS -- tCHAPTER 2. DURGA AND THE ROCK -- tCHAPTER 3. TRIBAL RECOGNITION -- tCHAPTER 4. INTERFACE -- tCHAPTER 5. SOFT SCIENCE IN HARD PLACES -- tCHAPTER 6. REFORMING THE SUBJECT -- tCHAPTER 7. PERPETUATED PARADIGMS -- tEPILOGUE. NEGOTIATING THE ETHNO-CONTEMPORARY -- tNOTES -- tBIBLIOGRAPHY -- tINDEX 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aSince the British colonial period anthropology has been central to policy in India. But today, while the Indian state continues to use ethnography to govern, those who were the "objects" of study are harnessing disciplinary knowledge to redefine their communities, achieve greater prosperity, and secure political rights. In this groundbreaking study, Townsend Middleton tracks these newfound "lives" of anthropology. Offering simultaneous ethnographies of the people of Darjeeling's quest for "tribal" status and the government anthropologists handling their claims, Middleton exposes how minorities are-and are not-recognized for affirmative action and autonomy. We encounter communities putting on elaborate spectacles of sacrifice, exorcism, bows and arrows, and blood drinking to prove their "primitiveness" and "backwardness." Conversely, we see government anthropologists struggle for the ethnographic truth as communities increasingly turn academic paradigms back upon the state. The Demands of Recognition offers a compelling look at the escalating politics of tribal recognition in India. At once ethnographic and historical, it chronicles how multicultural governance has motivated the people of Darjeeling to ethnologically redefine themselves-from Gorkha to tribal and back. But as these communities now know, not all forms of difference are legible in the eyes of the state. The Gorkhas' search for recognition has only amplified these communities' anxieties about who they are-and who they must be-if they are to attain the rights, autonomy, and belonging they desire.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aEthnicityxPolitical aspectszIndiazDarjeeling (District). 0aEthnologyxPolitical aspectszIndiazDarjeeling (District). 0aGorkha (South Asian people)zIndiazDarjeeling (District)xEthnic identity. 0aGorkha (South Asian people)zIndiazDarjeeling (District)xGovernment relations. 0aGorkha (South Asian people)zIndiazDarjeeling (District)xPolitics and government. 0aIdentity politicszIndiazDarjeeling (District). 4aAffirmative Action. 4aAutonomy. 4aBelonging. 4aDifference. 4aEthnology. 4aIdentity Politics. 4aIndigeneity (or 'Indigenous Movements'). 4aMulticulturalism. 4aPostcolonial State. 4aRecognition. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-